# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: secure-cookies
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:secure-cookies/document-cookie] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:secure-cookies/document-cookie] It’s been available across browsers since July 2019.
[src:secure-cookies/document-cookie] The `Document` property `cookie` lets you read and write cookies associated with the document.
[src:secure-cookies/document-cookie] It serves as a getter and setter for the actual values of the cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/document-cookie] A string containing a semicolon-separated list of all cookies (i.e., `key=value` pairs).
[src:secure-cookies/document-cookie] Note that each *key* and *value* may be surrounded by whitespace (space and tab characters): in fact, RFC 6265 mandates a single space after each semicolon, but some user agents may not abide by this.
[src:secure-cookies/document-cookie] You can also assign to this property a string of the form `"key=value"`, specifying the cookie to set/update.
[src:secure-cookies/document-cookie] Note that you can only set/update a single cookie at a time using this method.
[src:secure-cookies/document-cookie] In order to use the following code, please replace all occurrences of the word `doSomethingOnlyOnce` (the name of the cookie) with a custom name.
[src:secure-cookies/document-cookie] It is important to note that the `path` attribute does *not* protect against unauthorized reading of the cookie from a different path.
[src:secure-cookies/document-cookie] It can be easily bypassed using the DOM, for example by creating a hidden `<iframe>` element with the path of the cookie, then accessing this iframe's `contentDocument.cookie` property.
[src:secure-cookies/document-cookie] The only way to protect the cookie is by using a different domain or subdomain, due to the same origin policy.
[src:secure-cookies/document-cookie] Cookies are often used in web applications to identify a user and their authenticated session.
[src:secure-cookies/document-cookie] Stealing a cookie from a web application leads to hijacking the authenticated user's session.
[src:secure-cookies/document-cookie] The `HTTPOnly` cookie attribute can help to mitigate this attack by preventing access to cookie value through JavaScript.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] A **cookie** (also known as a web cookie or browser cookie) is a small piece of data a server sends to a user's web browser.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] The browser may store cookies, create new cookies, modify existing ones, and send them back to the same server with later requests.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] Cookies enable web applications to store limited amounts of data and remember state information; by default the HTTP protocol is stateless.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] In this article we will explore the main uses of cookies, explain best practices for using them, and look at their privacy and security implications.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] Typically, the server will use the contents of HTTP cookies to determine whether different requests come from the same browser/user and then issue a personalized or generic response as appropriate.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] If the credentials are correct, the server updates the UI to indicate that the user is signed in, and responds with a cookie containing a session ID that records their sign-in status on the browser.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] At a later time, the user moves to a different page on the same site.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] The browser sends the cookie containing the session ID along with the corresponding request to indicate that it still thinks the user is signed in.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] The server checks the session ID and, if it is still valid, sends the user a personalized version of the new page.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] If it is not valid, the session ID is deleted and the user is shown a generic version of the page (or perhaps shown an "access denied" message and asked to sign in again).
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] In the early days of the web when there was no other option, cookies were used for general client-side data storage purposes.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] Modern storage APIs are now recommended, for example the Web Storage API (`localStorage` and `sessionStorage`) and IndexedDB.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] After receiving an HTTP request, a server can send one or more `Set-Cookie` headers with the response, each one of which will set a separate cookie.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] You can specify an expiration date or time period after which the cookie should be deleted and no longer sent.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] To immediately remove a cookie, set the cookie again with the same name, path, and domain (if specified), and set its `Expires` attribute to a date in the past or its `Max-Age` attribute to `0` or negative.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] This instructs the browser to delete the cookie right away.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] You can also clear all cookies associated with a registrable domain using the `Clear-Site-Data` response header.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] For example, the following header sent from `https://foo.example.com/` would clear all cookies sent by `example.com` and all of its subdomains, such as `all.bar.example.com`.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] There are some techniques designed to recreate cookies after they're deleted.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] These techniques violate the principles of user privacy and control, may violate data privacy regulations, and could expose a website using them to legal liability.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] To update a cookie via HTTP, the server can send a `Set-Cookie` header with the existing cookie's name and a new value.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] There are several reasons why you might want to do this, for example if a user has updated their preferences and the application wants to reflect the changes in client-side data (you could also do this with a client-side storage mechanism such as Web Storage).
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] In the browser, you can create new cookies via JavaScript using the `Document.cookie` property, or the asynchronous Cookie Store API.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] Note that all examples below use `Document.cookie`, as it is the most widely supported/established option.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] For security purposes, you can't change cookie values by sending an updated `Cookie` header directly when initiating a request, for example, via `fetch()` or `XMLHttpRequest`.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] There are good reasons why you shouldn't allow JavaScript to modify cookies at all.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] You can prevent JavaScript from accessing a cookie by specifying the `HttpOnly` attribute during its creation.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] See the Security section for more details.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] When you store information in cookies, by default all cookie values are visible to, and can be changed by, the end user.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] You really don't want your cookies to be misused — for example accessed/modified by bad actors, or sent to domains where they shouldn't be sent.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] The potential consequences can range from annoying — apps not working or exhibiting strange behavior — to catastrophic.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] A criminal could for example steal a session ID and use it to set a cookie that makes it look like they are logged in as someone else, taking control of their bank or e-commerce account in the process.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] You can secure your cookies in a variety of ways, which are reviewed in this section.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] The `Domain` and `Path` attributes define the *scope* of a cookie: what URLs the cookies are sent to.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] The `SameSite` attribute lets servers specify whether/when cookies are sent with cross-site requests — i.e., third-party cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] Cross-site requests are requests where the site (the registrable domain) and/or the scheme (http or https) do not match the site the user is currently visiting.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] This includes requests sent when links are clicked on other sites to navigate to your site, and any request sent by embedded third-party content.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] `SameSite` helps to prevent leakage of information, preserving user privacy and providing some protection against cross-site request forgery attacks.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] If no `SameSite` attribute is set, the cookie is treated as `Lax` by default.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] Because of the design of the cookie mechanism, a server can't confirm that a cookie was set from a secure origin or even tell *where* a cookie was originally set.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] An application on a subdomain can set a cookie with the `Domain` attribute, which gives access to that cookie on all other subdomains.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] This mechanism can be abused in a session fixation attack.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] As a defense-in-depth measure, you can use *cookie prefixes* to impose specific restrictions on a cookie's attributes in supporting user-agents.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] All cookie prefixes start with a double-underscore (`__`) and end in a dash (`-`).
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] The browser will reject cookies with these prefixes that don't comply with their restrictions.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] As the application server only checks for a specific cookie name when determining if the user is authenticated or a CSRF token is correct, this effectively acts as a defense measure against session fixation.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] For more information about cookie prefixes and the current state of browser support, see the Prefixes section of the Set-Cookie reference article.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] Earlier on we talked about how the `SameSite` attribute can be used to control when third-party cookies are sent, and that this can help preserve user privacy.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] Privacy is a very important consideration when building websites which, when done right, can build trust with your users.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] If done badly, it can completely erode that trust and cause all kinds of other problems.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] Third-party cookies can be set by third-party content embedded in sites via `<iframe>`s.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] They have many legitimate uses include sharing user profile information, counting ad impressions, or collecting analytics across different related domains.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] However, third-party cookies can also be used to create creepy, invasive user experiences.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] A third-party server can create a profile of a user's browsing history and habits based on cookies sent to it by the same browser when accessing multiple sites.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] The classic example is when you search for product information on one site and are then chased around the web by adverts for similar products wherever you go.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] Browser vendors know that users don't like this behavior, and as a result have all started to block third-party cookies by default, or at least made plans to go in that direction.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] Third-party cookies (or just tracking cookies) may also be blocked by other browser settings or extensions.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] See our Third-party cookies article for detailed information on third-party cookies, the issues associated with them, and what alternatives are available.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] See our Privacy landing page for more information on privacy in general.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] They apply to any site on the *World Wide* Web that users from these jurisdictions access (the EU and California, with the caveat that California's law applies only to entities with gross revenue over 25 million USD, among things).
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] There may be other regulations that govern the use of cookies in your locality.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] The burden is on you to know and comply with these regulations.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-cookies] There are companies that offer "cookie banner" code that helps you comply with these regulations.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] The client sends its request, and waits for the answer.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] The server processes the request, sending back its answer, providing a status code and appropriate data.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] As of HTTP/1.1, the connection is no longer closed after completing the third phase, and the client is now granted a further request: this means the second and third phases can now be performed any number of times.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] In client-server protocols, it is the client which establishes the connection.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] Opening a connection in HTTP means initiating a connection in the underlying transport layer, usually this is TCP.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] With TCP, the default port for an HTTP server on a computer is port 80.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] Other ports can also be used, like 8000 or 8080.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] The URL of a page to fetch contains both the domain name, and the port number, though the latter can be omitted if it is 80.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] Once the connection is established, the user-agent can send the request (a user-agent is typically a web browser, but can be anything else, a crawler, for example).
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] Subsequent lines represent an HTTP header, giving the server information about what type of data is appropriate (for example, what language, what MIME types), or other data altering its behavior (for example, not sending an answer if it is already cached).
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] These HTTP headers form a block which ends with an empty line.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] The final block is an optional data block, which may contain further data mainly used by the POST method.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] Observe that final empty line, this separates the data block from the header block.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] As there is no `Content-Length` provided in an HTTP header, this data block is presented empty, marking the end of the headers, allowing the server to process the request the moment it receives this empty line.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] HTTP defines a set of request methods indicating the desired action to be performed upon a resource.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] Although they can also be nouns, these requests methods are sometimes referred as HTTP verbs.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] After the connected agent has sent its request, the web server processes it, and ultimately returns a response.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] Subsequent lines represent specific HTTP headers, giving the client information about the data sent (for example, type, data size, compression algorithm used, hints about caching).
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] Similarly to the block of HTTP headers for a client request, these HTTP headers form a block ending with an empty line.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] The final block is a data block, which contains the optional data.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] HTTP response status codes indicate if a specific HTTP request has been successfully completed.
[src:secure-cookies/guides-session] Responses are grouped into five classes: informational responses, successful responses, redirects, client errors, and server errors.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] The HTTP **`Set-Cookie`** response header is used to send a cookie from the server to the user agent, so that the user agent can send it back to the server later.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] To send multiple cookies, multiple `Set-Cookie` headers should be sent in the same response.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] When a Fetch API or XMLHttpRequest API request uses CORS, browsers will ignore `Set-Cookie` headers present in the server's response unless the request includes credentials.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Visit Using the Fetch API - Including credentials and the XMLHttpRequest article to learn how to include credentials.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] For more information, see the guide on Using HTTP cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] A cookie definition begins with a name-value pair.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] A `<cookie-value>` can optionally be wrapped in double quotes and include any US-ASCII character excluding control characters (ASCII characters 0 up to 31 and ASCII character 127), Whitespace, double quotes, commas, semicolons, and backslashes.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Defines the host to which the cookie will be sent.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Only the current domain can be set as the value, or a domain of a higher order, unless it is a public suffix.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Setting the domain will make the cookie available to it, as well as to all its subdomains.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] If omitted, the cookie is returned only to the host that sent them (i.e., it becomes a "host-only cookie").
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] This is more restrictive than setting the host name, as the cookie is not made available to subdomains of the host.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Contrary to earlier specifications, leading dots in domain names (`.example.com`) are ignored.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Multiple host/domain values are *not* allowed, but if a domain *is* specified, then subdomains are always included.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Indicates the maximum lifetime of the cookie as an HTTP-date timestamp.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] If unspecified, the cookie becomes a **session cookie**.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] A session finishes when the client shuts down, after which the session cookie is removed.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] The `Expires` attribute is set by the server with a value relative to its own internal clock, which may differ from that of the client browser.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Firefox and Chromium-based browsers internally use an expiry (max-age) value that is adjusted to compensate for clock difference, storing and expiring cookies based on the time intended by the server.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] The adjustment for clock skew is calculated from the value of the `DATE` header.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Note that the specification explains how the attribute should be parsed, but does not indicate if/how the value should be corrected by the recipient.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Forbids JavaScript from accessing the cookie, for example, through the `Document.cookie` property.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Note that a cookie that has been created with `HttpOnly` will still be sent with JavaScript-initiated requests, for example, when calling `XMLHttpRequest.send()` or `fetch()`.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] This mitigates attacks against cross-site scripting (XSS).
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Indicates the number of seconds until the cookie expires.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] A zero or negative number will expire the cookie immediately.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] If both `Expires` and `Max-Age` are set, `Max-Age` has precedence.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Indicates that the cookie should be stored using partitioned storage.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Note that if this is set, the `Secure` directive must also be set.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] See Cookies Having Independent Partitioned State (CHIPS) for more details.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Indicates the path that *must* exist in the requested URL for the browser to send the `Cookie` header.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] If omitted, this attribute defaults to the path component of the request URL.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] For example, if a cookie is set by a request to `https://example.com/docs/Web/HTTP/index.html`, the default path would be `/docs/Web/HTTP/`.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] The forward slash (`/`) character is interpreted as a directory separator, and subdirectories are matched as well.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Controls whether or not a cookie is sent with cross-site requests: that is, requests originating from a different site, including the scheme, from the site that set the cookie.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] This provides some protection against certain cross-site attacks, including cross-site request forgery (CSRF) attacks.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Send the cookie only for requests originating from the same site that set the cookie.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Some browsers use `Lax` as the default value if `SameSite` is not specified: see Browser compatibility for details.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Send the cookie with both cross-site and same-site requests.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] The `Secure` attribute must also be set when using this value.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Indicates that the cookie is sent to the server only when a request is made with the `https:` scheme (except on localhost), and therefore, is more resistant to man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Insecure sites (`http:`) cannot set cookies with the `Secure` attribute.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] The `https:` requirements are ignored when the `Secure` attribute is set by localhost.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Some cookie names contain prefixes that impose specific restrictions on the cookie's attributes in supporting user-agents.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Session cookies are removed when the client shuts down.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Cookies are session cookies if they do not specify the `Expires` or `Max-Age` attribute.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Permanent cookies are removed at a specific date (`Expires`) or after a specific length of time (`Max-Age`) and not when the client is closed.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] A cookie for a domain that does not include the server that set it should be rejected by the user agent.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] A cookie for a subdomain of the serving domain will be rejected.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Cookie names prefixed with `__Secure-` or `__Host-` can be used only if they are set with the `Secure` attribute from a secure (HTTPS) origin.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] Cookie names prefixed with `__Http-` or `__Host-Http-` can be used only if they are set with the `Secure` attribute from a secure (HTTPS) origin and in addition must have the `HttpOnly` attribute set to prove that they were set via the `Set-Cookie` header and not on the client-side via JavaScript.
[src:secure-cookies/headers-set-cookie] In addition, cookies with the `__Host-` or `__Host-Http-` prefix must have a path of `/` (meaning any path at the host) and must not have a `Domain` attribute.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] An **HTTP cookie** (also called **web cookie**, **Internet cookie**, **browser cookie**, or simply **cookie**) is a small block of data created by a web server while a user is browsing a website and placed on the user's computer or other device by the user's web browser.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Cookies are placed on the device used to access a website, and more than one cookie may be placed on a user's device during a session.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Cookies serve useful and sometimes essential functions on the web.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] They enable web servers to store stateful information (such as items added in the shopping cart in an online store) on the user's device or to track the user's browsing activity (including clicking particular buttons, logging in, or recording which pages were visited in the past).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] They can also be used to save information that the user previously entered into form fields, such as names, addresses, passwords, and payment card numbers for subsequent use.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The term *cookie* was coined by web-browser programmer Lou Montulli.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] It was derived from the term *magic cookie*, which is a packet of data a program receives and sends back unchanged, used by Unix programmers.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Magic cookies were already used in computing when computer programmer Lou Montulli had the idea of using them in web communications in June 1994.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] At the time, he was an employee of Netscape Communications, which was developing an e-commerce application for MCI.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Vint Cerf and John Klensin represented MCI in technical discussions with Netscape Communications.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] MCI did not want its servers to have to retain partial transaction states, which led them to ask Netscape to find a way to store that state in each user's computer instead.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Cookies provided a solution to the problem of reliably implementing a virtual shopping cart.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Together with John Giannandrea, Montulli wrote the initial Netscape cookie specification the same year.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Version 0.9beta of Mosaic Netscape, released on 13 October 1994, supported cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The first use of cookies (out of the labs) was checking whether visitors to the Netscape website had already visited the site.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Montulli applied for a patent for the cookie technology in 1995, which was granted in 1998.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Support for cookies was integrated with Internet Explorer in version 2, released in October 1995.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The introduction of cookies was not widely known to the public at the time.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In particular, cookies were accepted by default, and users were not notified of their presence.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The public learned about cookies after the *Financial Times* published an article about them on 12 February 1996.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In the same year, cookies received a lot of media attention, especially because of potential privacy implications.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Federal Trade Commission hearings in 1996 and 1997.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The development of the formal cookie specifications was already ongoing.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In particular, the first discussions about a formal specification started in April 1995 on the www-talk mailing list.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] A special working group within the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) was formed.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Two alternative proposals for introducing state in HTTP transactions had been proposed by Brian Behlendorf and David Kristol respectively.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] But the group, headed by Kristol himself and Lou Montulli, soon decided to use the Netscape specification as a starting point.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In February 1996, the working group identified third-party cookies as a considerable privacy threat.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The specification produced by the group was eventually published as RFC 2109 in February 1997.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] It specifies that third-party cookies were either not allowed at all, or at least not enabled by default.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] At this time, advertising companies were already using third-party cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The recommendation about third-party cookies of RFC 2109 was not followed by Netscape and Internet Explorer.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] RFC 2109 was superseded by RFC 2965 in October 2000.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] RFC 2965 added a `Set-Cookie2` header field, which informally came to be called "RFC 2965-style cookies" as opposed to the original `Set-Cookie` header field which was called "Netscape-style cookies".
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] `Set-Cookie2` was seldom used, however, and was deprecated in RFC 6265 in April 2011 which was written as a definitive specification for cookies as used in the real world.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] No modern browser recognizes the `Set-Cookie2` header field.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] A *session cookie* (also known as an *in-memory cookie*, *transient cookie* or *non-persistent cookie*) exists only in temporary memory while the user navigates a website.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies expire or are deleted when the user closes the web browser.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies are identified by the browser by the absence of an expiration date assigned to them.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] A *persistent cookie* expires at a specific date or after a specific length of time.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] For the persistent cookie's lifespan set by its creator, its information will be transmitted to the server every time the user visits the website that it belongs to, or every time the user views a resource belonging to that website from another website (such as an advertisement).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] For this reason, persistent cookies are sometimes referred to as *tracking cookies* because they can be used by advertisers to record information about a user's web browsing habits over an extended period of time.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Persistent cookies are also used for reasons such as keeping users logged into their accounts on websites, to avoid re-entering login credentials at every visit.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] A *secure cookie* can only be transmitted over an encrypted connection (i.e.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] They cannot be transmitted over unencrypted connections (i.e.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] This makes the cookie less likely to be exposed to cookie theft via eavesdropping.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] A cookie is made secure by adding the `Secure` flag to the cookie.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] An *http-only cookie* cannot be accessed by client-side APIs, such as JavaScript.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] This restriction eliminates the threat of cookie theft via cross-site scripting (XSS).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] However, the cookie remains vulnerable to cross-site tracing (XST) and cross-site request forgery (CSRF) attacks.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] A cookie is given this characteristic by adding the `HttpOnly` flag to the cookie.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In 2016 Google Chrome version 51 introduced a new kind of cookie with attribute `SameSite` with possible values of `Strict`, `Lax` or `None`.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] With attribute `SameSite=Strict`, the browsers would only send cookies to a target domain that is the same as the origin domain.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] This would effectively mitigate cross-site request forgery (CSRF) attacks.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] With `SameSite=Lax`, browsers would send cookies with requests to a target domain even it is different from the origin domain, but only for *safe* requests such as GET (POST is unsafe) and not third-party cookies (inside iframe).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Attribute `SameSite=None` would allow third-party (cross-site) cookies, however, most browsers require secure attribute on SameSite=None cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The Same-site cookie is incorporated into a new RFC draft for "Cookies: HTTP State Management Mechanism" to update RFC 6265 (if approved).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Chrome, Firefox, and Edge started to support Same-site cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The key of rollout is the treatment of existing cookies without the SameSite attribute defined, Chrome has been treating those existing cookies as if SameSite=None, this would let all website/applications run as before.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Google intended to change that default to `SameSite=Lax` in Chrome 80 planned to be released in February 2020, but due to potential for breakage of those applications/websites that rely on third-party/cross-site cookies and COVID-19 circumstances, Google postponed this change to Chrome 84.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] A *supercookie* is a cookie with an origin of a top-level domain (such as `.com`) or a public suffix (such as `.co.uk`).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Ordinary cookies, by contrast, have an origin of a specific domain name, such as `example.com`.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Supercookies can be a potential security concern and are therefore often blocked by web browsers.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] If unblocked by the browser, an attacker in control of a malicious website could set a supercookie and potentially disrupt or impersonate legitimate user requests to another website that shares the same top-level domain or public suffix as the malicious website.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] For example, a supercookie with an origin of `.com` could maliciously affect a request made to `example.com`, even if the cookie did not originate from `example.com`.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] This can be used to fake logins or change user information.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The Public Suffix List helps to mitigate the risk that supercookies pose.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The Public Suffix List is a cross-vendor initiative that aims to provide an accurate and up-to-date list of domain name suffixes.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Older versions of browsers may not have an up-to-date list, and will therefore be vulnerable to supercookies from certain domains.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The term *supercookie* is also used for tracking technologies that do not rely on HTTP cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Two such *supercookie* mechanisms were found on Microsoft websites in August 2011: cookie syncing that respawned MUID (machine unique identifier) cookies, and ETag cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Due to media attention, Microsoft later disabled this code.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In a 2021 blog post, Mozilla used the term *supercookie* to refer to the use of browser cache as a means of tracking users across sites.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Zero or more attributes (name/value pairs).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Attributes store information such as the cookie's expiration, domain, and flags (such as `Secure` and `HttpOnly`).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Cookies were originally introduced to provide a way for users to record items they want to purchase as they navigate throughout a website (a virtual *shopping cart* or *shopping basket*).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Today, however, the contents of a user's shopping cart are usually stored in a database on the server, rather than in a cookie on the client.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] To keep track of which user is assigned to which shopping cart, the server sends a cookie to the client that contains a unique session identifier (typically, a long string of random letters and numbers).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Because cookies are sent to the server with every request the client makes, that session identifier will be sent back to the server every time the user visits a new page on the website, which lets the server know which shopping cart to display to the user.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Another popular use of cookies is for logging into websites.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] When the user visits a website's login page, the web server typically sends the client a cookie containing a unique session identifier.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] When the user successfully logs in, the server remembers that that particular session identifier has been authenticated and grants the user access to its services.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Because session cookies only contain a unique session identifier, this makes the amount of personal information that a website can save about each user virtually limitless—the website is not limited to restrictions concerning how large a cookie can be.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies also help to improve page load times, since the amount of information in a session cookie is small and requires little bandwidth.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Cookies can be used to remember information about the user in order to show relevant content to that user over time.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] For example, a web server might send a cookie containing the username that was last used to log into a website, so that it may be filled in automatically the next time the user logs in.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Many websites use cookies for personalization based on the user's preferences.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Users select their preferences by entering them in a web form and submitting the form to the server.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The server encodes the preferences in a cookie and sends the cookie back to the browser.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] This way, every time the user accesses a page on the website, the server can personalize the page according to the user's preferences.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] For example, the Google search engine once used cookies to allow users (even non-registered ones) to decide how many search results per page they wanted to see.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Also, DuckDuckGo uses cookies to allow users to set the viewing preferences like colors of the web page.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Tracking cookies are used to track users' web browsing habits.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] This can also be done to some extent by using the IP address of the computer requesting the page or the referer field of the HTTP request header, but cookies allow for greater precision.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] From this point on, the cookie will automatically be sent by the browser to the server every time a new page from the site is requested.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The server not only sends the page as usual but also stores the URL of the requested page, the date/time of the request, and the cookie in a log file.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] By analyzing this log file, it is then possible to discover which pages the user has visited, in what sequence, and for how long.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Corporations exploit users' web habits by tracking cookies to collect information about buying habits.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The *Wall Street Journal* found that America's top fifty websites installed an average of sixty-four pieces of tracking technology onto computers, resulting in a total of 3,180 tracking files.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The data can then be collected and sold to bidding corporations.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Cookies are arbitrary pieces of data, usually chosen and first sent by the web server, and stored on the client computer by the web browser.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The browser then sends them back to the server with every request, introducing states (memory of previous events) into otherwise stateless HTTP transactions.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Without cookies, each retrieval of a web page or component of a web page would be an isolated event, largely unrelated to all other page views made by the user on the website.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Although cookies are usually set by the web server, they can also be set by the client using a scripting language such as JavaScript (unless the cookie's `HttpOnly` flag is set, in which case the cookie cannot be modified by scripting languages).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Cookies are set using the `Set-Cookie` header field, sent in an HTTP response from the web server.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] This header field instructs the web browser to store the cookie and send it back in future requests to the server (the browser will ignore this header field if it does not support cookies or has disabled cookies).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The server's HTTP response contains the contents of the website's homepage.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] But it also instructs the browser to set two cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The first, *theme*, is considered to be a *session cookie* since it does not have an `Expires` or `Max-Age` attribute.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies are intended to be deleted by the browser when the browser closes.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The second, *sessionToken*, is considered to be a *persistent cookie* since it contains an `Expires` attribute, which instructs the browser to delete the cookie at a specific date and time.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Next, the browser sends another request to visit the `spec.html` page on the website.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] This way, the server knows that this HTTP request is related to the previous one.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The server would answer by sending the requested page, possibly including more `Set-Cookie` header fields in the HTTP response in order to instruct the browser to add new cookies, modify existing cookies, or remove existing cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] To remove a cookie, the server must include a `Set-Cookie` header field with an expiration date in the past.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The value of a cookie may consist of any printable ASCII character (`!` through `~`, Unicode `\u0021` through `\u007E`) excluding `,`and`;` and whitespace characters.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The name of a cookie excludes the same characters, as well as `=`, since that is the delimiter between the name and value.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The cookie standard RFC 2965 is more restrictive but not implemented by browsers.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The term *cookie crumb* is sometimes used to refer to a cookie's name–value pair.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Cookies can also be set by scripting languages such as JavaScript that run within the browser.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In JavaScript, the object `document.cookie` is used for this purpose.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] For example, the instruction `document.cookie = "temperature=20"` creates a cookie of name *temperature* and value *20*.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In addition to a name and value, cookies can also have one or more attributes.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Browsers do not include cookie attributes in requests to the server—they only send the cookie's name and value.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Cookie attributes are used by browsers to determine when to delete a cookie, block a cookie or whether to send a cookie to the server.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The `Domain` and `Path` attributes define the scope of the cookie.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] They essentially tell the browser what website the cookie belongs to.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] For security reasons, cookies can only be set on the current resource's top domain and its subdomains, and not for another domain and its subdomains.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] For example, the website `example.org` cannot set a cookie that has a domain of `foo.com` because this would allow the website `example.org` to control the cookies of the domain `foo.com`.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] If a cookie's `Domain` and `Path` attributes are not specified by the server, they default to the domain and path of the resource that was requested.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] However, in most browsers there is a difference between a cookie set from `foo.com` without a domain, and a cookie set with the `foo.com` domain.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In the former case, the cookie will only be sent for requests to `foo.com`, also known as a host-only cookie.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In the latter case, all subdomains are also included (for example, `docs.foo.com`).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] A notable exception to this general rule is Edge prior to Windows 10 RS3 and Internet Explorer prior to IE 11 and Windows 10 RS4 (April 2018), which always sends cookies to subdomains regardless of whether the cookie was set with or without a domain.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Below is an example of some `Set-Cookie` header fields in the HTTP response of a website after a user logged in.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The first cookie, `LSID`, has no `Domain` attribute, and has a `Path` attribute set to `/accounts`.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] This tells the browser to use the cookie only when requesting pages contained in `docs.foo.com/accounts` (the domain is derived from the request domain).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The other two cookies, `HSID` and `SSID`, would be used when the browser requests any subdomain in `.foo.com` on any path (for example `www.foo.com/bar`).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The prepending dot is optional in recent standards, but can be added for compatibility with RFC 2109 based implementations.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The `Expires` attribute defines a specific date and time for when the browser should delete the cookie.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The date and time are specified in the form `Wdy, DD Mon YYYY HH:MM:SS GMT`, or in the form `Wdy, DD Mon YY HH:MM:SS GMT` for values of YY where YY is greater than or equal to 0 and less than or equal to 69.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Alternatively, the `Max-Age` attribute can be used to set the cookie's expiration as an interval of seconds in the future, relative to the time the browser received the cookie.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The first cookie, `lu`, is set to expire sometime on 15 January 2013.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] It will be used by the client browser until that time.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The second cookie, `made_write_conn`, does not have an expiration date, making it a session cookie.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] It will be deleted after the user closes their browser.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The third cookie, `reg_fb_gate`, has its value changed to *deleted*, with an expiration time in the past.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The browser will delete this cookie right away because its expiration time is in the past.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Note that cookie will only be deleted if the domain and path attributes in the `Set-Cookie` field match the values used when the cookie was created.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] As of 2016 Internet Explorer did not support `Max-Age`.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The `Secure` and `HttpOnly` attributes do not have associated values.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Rather, the presence of just their attribute names indicates that their behaviors should be enabled.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The `Secure` attribute is meant to keep cookie communication limited to encrypted transmission, directing browsers to use cookies only via secure/encrypted connections.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] However, if a web server sets a cookie with a secure attribute from a non-secure connection, the cookie can still be intercepted when it is sent to the user by man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Therefore, for maximum security, cookies with the Secure attribute should only be set over a secure connection.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The `HttpOnly` attribute directs browsers not to expose cookies through channels other than HTTP (and HTTPS) requests.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] This means that the cookie cannot be accessed via client-side scripting languages (notably JavaScript), and therefore cannot be stolen easily via cross-site scripting (a pervasive attack technique).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Most modern browsers support cookies and allow the user to disable them.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Add-on tools for managing cookie permissions also exist.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Cookies have some important implications for the privacy and anonymity of web users.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] While cookies are sent only to the server setting them or a server in the same Internet domain, a web page may contain images or other components stored on servers in other domains.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Cookies that are set during retrieval of these components are called *third-party cookies*.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] A third-party cookie, belongs to a domain different from the one shown in the address bar.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] This sort of cookie typically appears when web pages feature content from external websites, such as banner advertisements.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] This opens up the potential for tracking the user's browsing history and is used by advertisers to serve relevant advertisements to each user.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] As an example, suppose a user visits `www.example.org`.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] This website contains an advertisement from `ad.foxytracking.com`, which, when downloaded, sets a cookie belonging to the advertisement's domain (`ad.foxytracking.com`).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Then, the user visits another website, `www.foo.com`, which also contains an advertisement from `ad.foxytracking.com` and sets a cookie belonging to that domain (`ad.foxytracking.com`).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Eventually, both of these cookies will be sent to the advertiser when loading their advertisements or visiting their website.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The advertiser can then use these cookies to build up a browsing history of the user across all the websites that have ads from this advertiser, through the use of the HTTP referer header field.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] As of 2014, some websites were setting cookies readable for over 100 third-party domains.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] On average, a single website was setting 10 cookies, with a maximum number of cookies (first- and third-party) reaching over 800.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The older standards for cookies, RFC 2109 and RFC 2965, recommend that browsers should protect user privacy and not allow sharing of cookies between servers by default.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] However, the newer standard, RFC 6265, explicitly allows user agents to implement whichever third-party cookie policy they wish.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Most modern web browsers contain privacy settings that can block third-party cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Since 2020, Apple Safari, Firefox, and Brave block all third-party cookies by default.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Safari allows embedded sites to use Storage Access API to request permission to set first-party cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In May 2020, Google Chrome 83 introduced new features to block third-party cookies by default in its Incognito mode for private browsing, making blocking optional during normal browsing.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The same update also added an option to block first-party cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In April 2024, Chrome postponed third-party cookie blocking by default to 2025.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In July 2024, Google announced plan to avoid blocking third-party cookies by default and instead prompt users to allow third-party cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The possibility of building a profile of users is a privacy threat, especially when tracking is done across multiple domains using third-party cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] For this reason, some countries have legislation about cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Website operators who do not disclose third-party cookie use to consumers run the risk of harming consumer trust if cookie use is discovered.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Having clear disclosure (such as in a privacy policy) tends to eliminate any negative effects of such cookie discovery.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The government of the United States set strict rules on setting cookies in 2000 after it was disclosed that the White House drug policy office used cookies to track computer users viewing its online anti-drug advertising.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In 2002, privacy activist Daniel Brandt found that the CIA had been leaving persistent cookies on computers that had visited its website.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] When notified it was violating policy, CIA stated that these cookies were not intentionally set and stopped setting them.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] On 25 December 2005, Brandt discovered that the National Security Agency (NSA) had been leaving two persistent cookies on visitors' computers due to a software upgrade.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] After being informed, the NSA immediately disabled the cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In 2002, the European Union launched the Directive on Privacy and Electronic Communications (e-Privacy Directive), a policy requiring end users' consent for the placement of cookies, and similar technologies for storing and accessing information on users' equipment.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In particular, Article 5 Paragraph 3 mandates that storing technically unnecessary data on a user's computer can only be done if the user is provided information about how this data is used, and the user is given the possibility of denying this storage operation.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The Directive does not require users to authorise or be provided notice of cookie usage that are functionally required for delivering a service they have requested, for example to retain settings, store log-in sessions, or remember what is in a user's shopping basket.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In 2009, the law was amended by Directive 2009/136/EC, which included a change to Article 5, Paragraph 3.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Instead of having an option for users to opt out of cookie storage, the revised Directive requires consent to be obtained for cookie storage.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The definition of consent is cross-referenced to the definition in European data protection law, firstly the Data Protection Directive 1995 and subsequently the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] As the definition of consent was strengthened in the text of the GDPR, this increased the quality of consent required by those storing and accessing information such as cookies on users devices.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In a case decided under the Data Protection Directive however, the Court of Justice of the European Union later confirmed however that the previous law implied the same strong quality of consent as the current instrument.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In addition to the requirement of consent which stems from storing or accessing information on a user's terminal device, the information in many cookies will be considered personal data under the GDPR alone, and will require a legal basis to process.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] This has been the case since the 1995 Data Protection Directive, which used an identical definition of personal data, although the GDPR in interpretative Recital 30 clarifies that cookie identifiers are included.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] While not all data processing under the GDPR requires consent, the characteristics of behavioural advertising mean that it is difficult or impossible to justify under any other ground.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Consent under the combination of the GDPR and e-Privacy Directive has to meet a number of conditions in relation to cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] It must be freely given and unambiguous: preticked boxes were banned under both the Data Protection Directive 1995 and the GDPR (Recital 32).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The GDPR is specific that consent must be as 'easy to withdraw as to give', meaning that a reject-all button must be as easy to access in terms of clicks and visibility as an 'accept all' button.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] It must be specific and informed, meaning that consent relates to particular purposes for the use of this data, and all organisations seeking to use this consent must be specifically named.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The Court of Justice of the European Union has also ruled that consent must be 'efficient and timely', meaning that it must be gained before cookies are laid and data processing begins instead of afterwards.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The industry's response has been largely negative.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Robert Bond of the law firm Speechly Bircham describes the effects as "far-reaching and incredibly onerous" for "all UK companies".
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Simon Davis of Privacy International argues that proper enforcement would "destroy the entire industry".
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] However, scholars note that the onerous nature of cookie pop-ups stems from an attempt to continue to operate a business model through convoluted requests that may be incompatible with the GDPR.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Academic studies and regulators both describe widespread non-compliance with the law.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] A study scraping 10,000 UK websites found that only 11.8% of sites adhered to minimal legal requirements, with only 33.4% of websites studied providing a mechanism to reject cookies that was as easy to use as accepting them.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] A study of 17,000 websites found that 84% of sites breached this criterion, finding additionally that many laid third party cookies with no notice at all.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] A W3C specification called P3P was proposed for servers to communicate their privacy policy to browsers, allowing automatic, user-configurable handling.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] However, few websites implement the specification, and the W3C has discontinued work on the specification.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Third-party cookies can be blocked by most browsers to increase privacy and reduce tracking by advertising and tracking companies without negatively affecting the user's web experience on all sites.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Some sites operate 'cookie walls', which make access to a site conditional on allowing cookies either technically in a browser, through pressing 'accept', or both.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In 2020, the European Data Protection Board, composed of all EU data protection regulators, stated that cookie walls were illegal.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Many advertising operators have an opt-out option to behavioural advertising, with a generic cookie in the browser stopping behavioural advertising.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] However, this is often ineffective against many forms of tracking, such as first-party tracking that is growing in popularity to avoid the impact of browsers blocking third party cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Furthermore, if such a setting is more difficult to place than the acceptance of tracking, it remains in breach of the conditions of the e-Privacy Directive.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Most websites use cookies as the only identifiers for user sessions, because other methods of identifying web users have limitations and vulnerabilities.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] If a website uses cookies as session identifiers, attackers can impersonate users' requests by stealing a full set of victims' cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] From the web server's point of view, a request from an attacker then has the same authentication as the victim's requests; thus the request is performed on behalf of the victim's session.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Listed here are various scenarios of cookie theft and user session hijacking (even without stealing user cookies) that work with websites relying solely on HTTP cookies for user identification.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Traffic on a network can be intercepted and read by computers on the network other than the sender and receiver (particularly over unencrypted open Wi-Fi).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] This traffic includes cookies sent on ordinary unencrypted HTTP sessions.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Where network traffic is not encrypted, attackers can therefore read the communications of other users on the network, including HTTP cookies as well as the entire contents of the conversations, for the purpose of a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] An attacker could use intercepted cookies to impersonate a user and perform a malicious task, such as transferring money out of the victim's bank account.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] This issue can be resolved by securing the communication between the user's computer and the server by employing Transport Layer Security (HTTPS protocol) to encrypt the connection.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] A server can specify the `Secure` flag while setting a cookie, which will cause the browser to send the cookie only over an encrypted channel, such as a TLS connection.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] If an attacker is able to cause a DNS server to cache a fabricated DNS entry (called DNS cache poisoning), then this could allow the attacker to gain access to a user's cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] For example, an attacker could use DNS cache poisoning to create a fabricated DNS entry of `f12345.www.example.com` that points to the IP address of the attacker's server.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The attacker can then post an image URL from his own server (for example, `http://f12345.www.example.com/img_4_cookie.jpg`).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Victims reading the attacker's message would download this image from `f12345.www.example.com`.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Since `f12345.www.example.com` is a sub-domain of `www.example.com`, victims' browsers would submit all `example.com`-related cookies to the attacker's server.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] If an attacker is able to accomplish this, it is usually the fault of the Internet service providers for not properly securing their DNS servers.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] However, the severity of this attack can be lessened if the target website uses secure cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In this case, the attacker would have the extra challenge of obtaining the target website's TLS certificate from a certificate authority, since secure cookies can only be transmitted over an encrypted connection.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Without a matching TLS certificate, victims' browsers would display a warning message about the attacker's invalid certificate, which would help deter users from visiting the attacker's fraudulent website and sending the attacker their cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Cookies can also be stolen using a technique called cross-site scripting.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] This occurs when an attacker takes advantage of a website that allows its users to post unfiltered HTML and JavaScript content.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] By posting malicious HTML and JavaScript code, the attacker can cause the victim's web browser to send the victim's cookies to a website the attacker controls.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] When another user clicks on this link, the browser executes the piece of code within the `onclick` attribute, thus replacing the string `document.cookie` with the list of cookies that are accessible from the current page.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] As a result, this list of cookies is sent to the `attacker.com` server.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] If the attacker's malicious posting is on an HTTPS website `https://www.example.com`, secure cookies will also be sent to attacker.com in plain text.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] It is the responsibility of the website developers to filter out such malicious code.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Such attacks can be mitigated by using HttpOnly cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] These cookies will not be accessible by client-side scripting languages like JavaScript, and therefore, the attacker will not be able to gather these cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In older versions of many browsers, there were security holes in the implementation of the XMLHttpRequest API.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] This API allows pages to specify a proxy server that would get the reply, and this proxy server is not subject to the same-origin policy.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] For example, a victim is reading an attacker's posting on `www.example.com`, and the attacker's script is executed in the victim's browser.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] The script generates a request to `www.example.com` with the proxy server `attacker.com`.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Since the request is for `www.example.com`, all `example.com` cookies will be sent along with the request, but routed through the attacker's proxy server.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Hence, the attacker would be able to harvest the victim's cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] This attack would not work with secure cookies, since they can only be transmitted over HTTPS connections, and the HTTPS protocol dictates end-to-end encryption (i.e. the information is encrypted on the user's browser and decrypted on the destination server).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In this case, the proxy server would only see the raw, encrypted bytes of the HTTP request.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] For example, Bob might be browsing a chat forum where another user, Mallory, has posted a message.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] If Bob's bank keeps his authentication information in a cookie, and if the cookie hasn't expired, then the attempt by Bob's browser to load the image will submit the withdrawal form with his cookie, thus authorizing a transaction without Bob's approval.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Besides privacy concerns, cookies also have some technical drawbacks.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] In particular, they do not always accurately identify users, they can be used for security attacks, and they are often at odds with the Representational State Transfer (REST) software architectural style.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] If more than one browser is used on a computer, each usually has a separate storage area for cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Hence, cookies do not identify a person, but a combination of a user account, a computer, and a web browser.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Thus, anyone who uses multiple accounts, computers, or browsers has multiple sets of cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p01] Likewise, cookies do not differentiate between multiple users who share the same user account, computer, and browser.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Some of the operations that can be done using cookies can also be done using other mechanisms.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] A JSON Web Token (JWT) is a self-contained packet of information that can be used to store user identity and authenticity information.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] This allows them to be used in place of session cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Unlike cookies, which are automatically attached to each HTTP request by the browser, JWTs must be explicitly attached to each HTTP request by the web application.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] The HTTP protocol includes the basic access authentication and the digest access authentication protocols, which allow access to a web page only when the user has provided the correct username and password.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] If the server requires such credentials for granting access to a web page, the browser requests them from the user and, once obtained, the browser stores and sends them in every subsequent page request.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] This information can be used to track the user.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] The query string part of the URL is the part that is typically used for this purpose, but other parts can be used as well.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] The Java Servlet and PHP session mechanisms both use this method if cookies are not enabled.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] This method consists of the web server appending query strings containing a unique session identifier to all the links inside of a web page.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] When the user follows a link, the browser sends the query string to the server, allowing the server to identify the user and maintain state.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] These kinds of query strings are very similar to cookies in that both contain arbitrary pieces of information chosen by the server and both are sent back to the server on every request.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Since a query string is part of a URL, if that URL is later reused, the same attached piece of information will be sent to the server, which could lead to confusion.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] For example, if the preferences of a user are encoded in the query string of a URL and the user sends this URL to another user by e-mail, those preferences will be used for that other user as well.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Moreover, if the same user accesses the same page multiple times from different sources, there is no guarantee that the same query string will be used each time.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] For example, if a user visits a page by coming from a page *internal to the site* the first time, and then visits the same page by coming from an *external search engine* the second time, the query strings would likely be different.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] If cookies were used in this situation, the cookies would be the same.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Other drawbacks of query strings are related to security.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Storing data that identifies a session in a query string enables session fixation attacks, referer logging attacks and other security exploits.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Transferring session identifiers as HTTP cookies is more secure.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Another form of session tracking is to use web forms with hidden fields.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] This technique is very similar to using URL query strings to hold the information and has many of the same advantages and drawbacks.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] In fact, if the form is handled with the HTTP GET method, then this technique is similar to using URL query strings, since the GET method adds the form fields to the URL as a query string.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] But most forms are handled with HTTP POST, which causes the form information, including the hidden fields, to be sent in the HTTP request body, which is neither part of the URL, nor of a cookie.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] This approach presents two advantages from the point of view of the tracker.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] First, having the tracking information placed in the HTTP request body rather than in the URL means it will not be noticed by the average user.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Second, the session information is not copied when the user copies the URL (to bookmark the page or send it via email, for example).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] All current web browsers can store a fairly large amount of data (2–32 MB) via JavaScript using the DOM property `window.name`.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] This data can be used instead of session cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] The technique can be coupled with JSON/JavaScript objects to store complex sets of session variables on the client side.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] The downside is that every separate window or tab will initially have an empty `window.name` property when opened.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] In some respects, this can be more secure than cookies because its contents are not automatically sent to the server on every request like cookies are, so it is not vulnerable to network cookie sniffing attacks.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Some users may be tracked based on the IP address of the computer requesting the page.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] The server knows the IP address of the computer running the browser (or the proxy, if any is used) and could theoretically link a user's session to this IP address.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] However, IP addresses are generally not a reliable way to track a session or identify a user.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Many computers designed to be used by a single user, such as office PCs or home PCs, are behind a network address translator (NAT).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] This means that several PCs will share a public IP address.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Furthermore, some systems, such as Tor, are designed to retain Internet anonymity, rendering tracking by IP address impractical, impossible, or a security risk.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Because ETags are cached by the browser, and returned with subsequent requests for the same resource, a tracking server can simply repeat any ETag received from the browser to ensure an assigned ETag persists indefinitely (in a similar way to persistent cookies).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Additional caching header fields can also enhance the preservation of ETag data.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] ETags can be flushed in some browsers by clearing the browser cache.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] The browser cache can also be used to store information that can be used to track individual users.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] This technique takes advantage of the fact that the web browser will use resources stored within the cache instead of downloading them from the website when it determines that the cache already has the most up-to-date version of the resource.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] For example, a website could serve a JavaScript file with code that sets a unique identifier for the user (for example, `var userId = 3243242;`).
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] After the user's initial visit, every time the user accesses the page, this file will be loaded from the cache instead of downloaded from the server.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] A browser fingerprint is information collected about a browser's configuration, such as version number, screen resolution, and operating system, for the purpose of identification.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Fingerprints can be used to fully or partially identify individual users or devices even when cookies are turned off.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Basic web browser configuration information has long been collected by web analytics services in an effort to accurately measure real human web traffic and discount various forms of click fraud.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] With the assistance of client-side scripting languages, collection of much more esoteric parameters is possible.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Assimilation of such information into a single string constitutes a device fingerprint.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] In 2010, EFF measured at least 18.1 bits of entropy possible from browser fingerprinting.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Canvas fingerprinting, a more recent technique, claims to add another 5.7 bits.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Some web browsers support persistence mechanisms which allow the page to store the information locally for later use.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] The HTML5 standard (which most modern web browsers support to some extent) includes a JavaScript API called Web storage that allows two types of storage: local storage and session storage.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Local storage behaves similarly to persistent cookies while session storage behaves similarly to session cookies, except that session storage is tied to an individual tab/window's lifetime (AKA a page session), not to a whole browser session like session cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Internet Explorer supports persistent information in the browser's history, in the browser's favorites, in an XML store ("user data"), or directly within a web page saved to disk.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] Some web browser plugins include persistence mechanisms as well.
[src:secure-cookies/http-cookie-p02] For example, Adobe Flash has Local shared object and Microsoft Silverlight has Isolated storage.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] Although seemingly useful for protecting cookies from active network attackers, the Secure attribute protects only the cookie's confidentiality.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] An active network attacker can overwrite Secure cookies from an insecure channel, disrupting their integrity.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] This issue is officially referred to as Weak Integrity.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] However, some browsers, including Chrome 52 and higher and Firefox 52 and higher, forgo this specification in favor of better security and forbid insecure sites (HTTP) from setting cookies with the `Secure` directive.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] Even with `Secure`, some sources recommend that sensitive information *never* be stored in cookies, on the premise that they are inherently insecure and this flag can't offer real protection.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] Secure attribute is not the only protection mechanism for cookies, there are also HttpOnly and SameSite attributes.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] The HttpOnly attribute restricts the cookie from being accessed by, for instance, JavaScript, while the SameSite attribute only allows the cookie to be sent to the application if the request originated from the same domain.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] An HTTP cookie is a small packet of data that is sent from a web server to a user's web browser.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] Cookies could contain sensitive information, such as passwords and credit card numbers, which are sent over an HTTP connection and might be stored in web browsers as plain text.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] To prevent attackers from stealing this information, cookies can be secured with attributes.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] Various cookie hijacking techniques exist.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] The methods are not difficult to implement and can do significant damage to a user or an organization.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] Cookies that contain sensitive information such as usernames, passwords, and session identifiers can be captured using these tools once they are downloaded from a site to a web browser or accessed through a computer hard drive.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] Cookies that are sent over unencrypted channels can be subject to eavesdropping, i.e. the contents of the cookie can be read by the attacker.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] These types of threats can be prevented by the use of transport layer security in servers and web browsers, although this works only if the cookies are on the network.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] One might also use cookies with only the sensitive information encrypted instead of the entirety of a data payload exchanged.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] Cookies can be stolen or copied from the user, which could either reveal the information in the cookies or allow the attacker to edit the contents of the cookies and impersonate the users.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] This happens when a cookie, which is in the browser's end system and stored in the local drive or memory in clear text, is altered or copied from one computer to another with or without the knowledge of the user.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] An attacker can try to impersonate a website by accepting cookies from the users.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] Once the attacker gets the cookies, he can use these harvested cookies for websites that accept third-party cookies.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] An example of this threat is the so-called Cross-Site Scripting attack, which involves the exploitation of the vulnerabilities of a website displaying data provided by the user that has underlying malicious intent.
[src:secure-cookies/secure-cookie] An attacker, for instance, could embed a script in a URL he has posted in a discussion forum, message board, or email, which is then activated when the target opens the hyperlink.
